[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Investigating test coverage issues**\n\nI need to reflect on our testing process because the user repeats a task that we didn’t cover. It seems our tests may not adapt well under dynamic access due to potential naming issues with a nested class. I should inspect the current file for any naming conflicts, especially since our public API has specific conventions. \n\nAlso, it seems like our testing didn’t execute correctly under native reports, and I need to figure out if that’s why we aren't seeing dynamic access in our results.\n\n**Examining test coverage outcomes**\n\nI’m looking at the tests which only failed on assertions, but the report indicates there’s no new coverage. This might stem from the workflow following the attempt. I need to refine the dynamic access reporting, especially since it seems to track calls correctly. \n\nIf tests execute Java methods, they should be covered, but maybe they’re not under native-image settings where the calls are resolved at the build time. I’ll need to check if existing tests are calling the correct methods during function creation.\n\n**Clarifying native image build issues**\n\nI’m looking into the native-image build, which includes test classes, but I wonder if HSQLDB supports Java methods only when a certain system property is set. It seems like the dynamic access report may only capture calls from the library jar, not from tests. \n\nThe issue could be that HSQLDB's `Routine.getMethods` isn't called in native tests because functions are created during the JVM test, not the native test. As the TCK command runs the test first, which failed, it may explain the lack of coverage. I need to ensure tests pass first before proceeding.\n\n**Refining testing methods**\n\nI need to refine my approach here. I'm considering whether we should leverage a direct function using public static methods in a top-level test helper class instead of using nested `RoutineMethods`. There are naming conventions for dynamic access metadata that use `$`, and it might not be ideal for test class names. It might be better to have a top-level `RoutineMethods` class in its own file while keeping the test file structure clean. I think this will improve overall configuration!\n\n**Organizing test classes**\n\nI'm figuring out the best way to structure my test classes. I think using a `final class RoutineMethods` as package-private in the same file could work, but I need to be sure it won't be included by JUnit. Also, I should avoid public static nested classes. Moving `RoutineMethods` and `StringArray` out of `RoutineTest` should help, especially since referencing `RoutineMethods.class.getName()` now properly avoids the `$`. I’ve got some editing to do, particularly for HSQLDB reflection metadata in native images!\n\n**Exploring HSQLDB options**\n\nI'm considering making a helper public nested in order to get reflection to work. However, the class name has a `$`, which complicates things since it doesn't match the file or test class. An alternative could be to use a public library class method within HSQLDB to avoid dealing with the test reflection metadata and the `$`. There are several public static methods in HSQLDB that have SQL-compatible signatures, so I think I'll check out `org.hsqldb.Library`.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_00b1e1f45b47f6430169f16e3b93108197a344dc3cc76539b5\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp8W5TyQwczwrDdKz2zg3rWFYR7yW2tW9I9ZQiTY1Dt2Ww3e1A5YfDqLzbqXasaXEb7YVjqnzt6wUYRT5Cjfdq3EcNvuPJVF-rg0w49QnYbaQtXfZ1nclAd_1H8qbm0kRLHw5Qqb-GSxswLJCd45uEnsmDo3iS2h1bF1MKgs6Vga3-TqMzJj88tJN-4YLf7HjAI7Zg6cqQEaZuTc7sGMEY31QVfxHy2es2Be-gvqPCvyr-0wawKqmKfUcBTNL5Zrx_EdH3DbCmn4BWuGE38pBn-sNLkUId22WIXx3ak4Re7HwbOo-KijcZeTlzUIR-LN7mmI5xAxCbK4vQefSD-q4YK9uDyhx17hrjxc6imxcrHumHV-5AdlK3W9l-hv5xipCOE4reuI3sJ1aqRIzPXbuUhT53OkWvBzi_PLF_tCqsLJ5u3Rn8MX1x8-VWQNQHiBlSxqvkaIDUZnNMyUHiSyW34BE